TEXT ORDER - Entered by Judge Sara Darrow on 6/17/2016. On June 7, 2016, the Plaintiff sent a letter to the Court complaining about problems at Pontiac Correctional Center. 1 The letter was filed as a complaint pursuant to 42 U.S.C. ยง1983. see Bahler v Lopez, 2007 WL 1375924 (7th Cir. May 10, 2007)(clerk may not refuse pro se plaintiff's initial submission, a letter, for failing to follow Fed.R.Civ.P 8). However, it was not clear to the Court whether Plaintiff intended to file a lawsuit. Therefore, the Court gave the Plaintiff until June 29, 2016 to clarify his intentions in writing. ORDER FOR CONSOLIDATION AND APPOINTMENT OF CO-LEAD PLAINTIFFS AND CO-LEAD COUNSEL - IT IS ORDERED that the Joint Motion for Consolidation of Related Actions and Appointment of Co-Lead Plaintiffs and Co-Lead Counsel (Filing No. 22 in Case No. 4:17CV441; Filing No. 22 in Case No. 4:17CV3152) is granted. The parties Stipulation for Consolidation of Related Actions and Appointment of Co-Lead Plaintiffs and Co-Lead Counsel (Filing No. 23 in Case No. 4:17CV441; Filing No. 23 in Case No. 4:17CV3152) is adopted. The Gennaro Action and the Gerson Action shall be consolidated for all purposes, herein referred to as the "Consolidated Action." The law firms of Kessler Topaz Meltzer & Check, LLP and Labaton Sucharow LLP will serve as co-lead counsel for Plaintiffs in the Consolidated Action. Anthony Gennaro, Jr. and James D. Gerson shall serve as co-lead plaintiffs in the Consolidated Action. The Bruning Law Group shall serve as liaison counsel in the Consolidated Action. Hereafter, papers only need to be filed in Case No. 4:17-cv-00441-JMG-MDN. All documents previously filed to date in either of the Gennaro Action or Gerson Action are deemed filed and are a part of the record in the Consolidated Action. Defendants shall have no obligation to respond or file an answer to the complaints filed in the Gennaro Action and Gerson Action. A consolidated amended complaint shall be filed in the Consolidated Action and shall be deemed the operative complaint and shall supersede all previous complaints filed in any of the Gennaro Action or the Gerson Action, or any other action subsequently consolidated herewith. Defendants shall answer or move to dismiss the consolidated amended complaint within thirty (30) days of the filing of the consolidated amended complaint. This Order shall apply to this Consolidated Action and any future-filed actions relating to the subject matter of this case. When a case that properly belongs as part of the Consolidated Action is hereafter filed in the Court, this Court requests the assistance of Co-Lead Counsel in calling to the attention of the Court the filing of any case which might properly be consolidated as part of the Consolidated Action, and Co-Lead Counsel is to assist in assuring that counsel in subsequent actions receive notice of this Order. Ordered by Magistrate Judge Michael D. Nelson. (TCL) (Entered: 11/30/2017)

MEMORANDUM OPINION AND ORDER: Plaintiff's complaint is dismissed without prejudice for failure to prosecute and for counsel's failure to comply with numerous orders of the Court. In dismissing this case, the Court echoes an observation made by Judge Brian Cogan of the United States District Court for the Eastern District of New York last year in another ADA accessibility case brought by Plaintiff's counsel: "The Court understands that plaintiff's counsel runs these cases on a volume basis and that is her business, but she must utilize reasonable process to get each case moving before this Court and cannot allow these scenarios to repeat themselves anymore. It is almost as if she is deliberately filing papers that cannot move the case forward in order to unreasonably delay it. Whether deliberate or not, she has to stop it, both in this case and in the others that she brings before this Court." Taylor v. Happy M.E.W.S. Inc., No. 15-cv-5410 (BMC) (Dkt. No. 13). The Clerk of Court is directed to terminate all pending motions and to close this case. The Clerk of Court is further directed to send a copy of this order to Defendant by certified mail. (Signed by Judge Gregory H. Woods on 12/14/2016) (cla) (Entered: 12/14/2016)

Minute Entry & Notation Order: This case came before the Court for a status conference by telephone on 12/27/2016 at 1:30 p.m. Attorneys Tim Mangan and Brad Kraemer participated. The case against co-Defendant Luis Martinez Melo (2) was transferred to the Eastern District of Tennessee, for disposition pursuant to Fed. R. Crim. P. 20. As to Defendant Luis Caseres-Duarte (1), the Government states, and Defendant confirms, that all discovery was previously provided and that the parties are currently engaged in plea negotiations. Defense counsel stated that the case is likely to resolve by way of a plea agreement. The Court sets this case for a status conference by telephone on 1/27/2017 at 10:00 a.m. COUNSEL SHALL CALL: 1-888-684-8852; Access Code: 8411435; Security Code 123456, and wait for the Court to join the conference. If, prior to the conference, the parties have filed a signed plea agreement, the Court will convert the status conference to a change of plea hearing. As the parties are engaged in active plea negotiations, the time elapsing from 12/27/2016 through 1/27/2017 shall be EXCLUDED from the speedy trial computation. United States v. Montgomery, 395 F. App'x 177, 182 (6th Cir. 2010) ("plea negotiations are an example of 'other proceedings' not specifically listed in ยง 3161(h)(1) which may be excluded from the Speedy Trial Act calculation"). IT IS SO ORDERED. (Court Reporter: Mary Ann Ranz (Official)) (mr) (Entered: 12/27/2016)

After balancing the factors discussed in United States v. JUDGMENT as to Delanor Lamont Simmons (1), Count(s) 1,2,3,5: The defendant is hereby committed to the custody of the Federal Bureau of Prisons to be imprisoned for a total term of ONE HUNDRED TWENTY (120) months. Said terms consists of 60 months as to Counts 1, 2 and 3, all to run concurrently and 60 months as to Count 5, to run consecutively to all other counts. The defendant shall pay the mandatory $400.00 special assessment fee, due beginning immediately. The court makes the following recommendations to the Bureau of Prisons: The defendant be considered for the RDAP program. Defendant be designated to FCI Jesup or FCI, Butner. The defendant is remanded to the custody of the United States Marshal. Upon release from imprisonment, the defendant shall be on supervised release for a term of FIVE (5) years. Said term consist of 5 years as to Counts 1 and 2, 4 years as to Count 3, and 2 years as to Count 5, all to run concurrently. While on supervised release, the defendant shall comply with the mandatory and standard conditions of supervision outlined in 18 U.S.C. ยง3583 (d). The defendant shall also comply with the following special conditions for the reasons set forth in the presentence report which has previously been adopted by the Court as the finding of facts for the purposes of sentencing: 1. The defendant shall participate in a program of testing for substance abuse as approved by the U.S. Probation Officer. 2.The defendant shall satisfactorily participate in and complete a Cognitive Behavioral Treatment Program as approved by the U.S. Probation Office. 3. The defendant shall enroll in and complete an accredited educational program as approved by the U.S. Probation Officer with the objective of obtaining a GED, unless already obtained during the period of incarceration. 4.The defendant shall contribute to the costs of any treatment, drug testing and/or location monitoring not to exceed an amount determined reasonable by the court approved U.S. Probation Offices Sliding Scale for Services, and shall cooperate in securing any applicable third-party payment, such as insurance or Medicaid. You must cooperate in the collection of DNA as directed by the probation officer. Count(s) 4, Dismissed on motion of the government. Signed by Honorable Richard M Gergel on 6/14/2018. (erav, ) (Entered: 06/14/2018)

MINUTE entry before Honorable Suzanne B. Conlon: Plaintiff Steven Lundy does not respond to defendant Russell Larson's motion to dismiss Counts II (Section 1985 conspiracy), III (defamation), and IV (malicious prosecution) of the second amended complaint pursuant to Fed. R. Civ. P. 12(b)(6). The uncontested motion to dismiss 34 is granted in part and denied in part. Larson states plausible bases to dismiss Counts II and III. Kirksey v. R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., 168 F.3d 1039, 1041 (7th Cir. 1999). Count IV for malicious prosecution stands. Collateral estoppel does not bar the malicious prosecution claim; Larson fails to establish as a matter of law that Lundy's stipulation of probable cause to proceed with a suspension hearing before the City of Calumet City police commissioner board is identical to probable cause to initiate a criminal proceeding against Lundy. Hukic v. Aurora Loan Servs., 588 F. 3d 420, 431 (7th Cir. 2009). Larson must answer Counts I (Section 1983 first amendment violation) and IV (malicious prosecution) by February 16, 2010. Mailed notice(air, ) (Entered: 02/04/2010)

Entry on Post-Trial Motions - While the Court has great sympathy for Bohanon and the harm he suffered, the City's policies did not give "rise to the harm" as required under Monell; rather, "the harm resulted from the acts of the [City's] agents." See Glisson, 849 F.3d at 379. The City's Motion for Judgment as a Matter of Law ECF No. 213 is granted. The City's Motion for New Trial or to Amend Judgment ECF No. 215 is denied as moot. Plaintiff's Motion for Award of Attorneys' Fees and Expense ECF No. 204 and 33 Plaintiff's Motion for Supplemental Award of Attorney's Fees ECF No. 240 are denied as moot. ***SEE ORDER FOR ADDITIONAL INFORMATION*** Signed by Judge James R. Sweeney II on 9/30/2020. (JDC) (Entered: 09/30/2020)
